{{Hinduism}}
'''Aksharaaabhyasam''' or '''Akshara abhyaasam''' or '''Vidyaarambham''' is a traditional religious function in which the child is given initiation of education so that the child is ready to receive formal education. This ritual involves [[Saraswati|Goddess Saraswati]] puja.<ref>{{cite news |title= Shopping month is here|author= |url= http://www.hindu.com/2009/07/13/stories/2009071351290200.htm|newspaper= The Hindu|date= |accessdate=6 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title= Devotees put to hardship at Basar|author= P. Ram Mohan|url= http://www.hindu.com/2008/02/12/stories/2008021254290400.htm|newspaper= The Hindu|date= |accessdate=6 February 2012}}</ref>
This ritual very common in Hindu families of [[Karnataka]], [[Kerala]], [[Andhra Pradesh]] and [[Telangana]]. Akshara means 'letters / alphabets' and Abhyasam means 'practice'. Together they mean "the study of practical letters". The ceremony is performed by the maternal uncle (Mothers brothers)/ Father/ Paternal Uncle along with the family keeping the child in his lap holding the child’s right hand forefinger and make the child write the [[Om]] followed by the panchaakshari mantra 'Namah Shivayaah'. In kerala Om Harisree Ganapathaye Namah mantra is used.
[[Om]] symbol which is treated as a Beejaakshar ([[Bīja|Beeja]] in [[Sanskrit]] means the origin). [[Gnana Saraswati Temple, Basar|Gnana Saraswati Temple]] in [[Basar, Andhra Pradesh|Basar]], [[Telangana]] is a popular temple where such ceremonies are held in large numbers.<ref>{{cite news |title= `Aksharabhyasam' launched|author= |url=http://www.hindu.com/2007/01/24/stories/2007012417900400.htm |newspaper= The Hindu|date= |accessdate=6 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title= Pilgrims throng Basar on Vasantha Panchami|author= |url= http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-02-09/india/28542713_1_basar-devotees-aksharabhyasam|newspaper= Times of India|date= |accessdate=6 February 2012}}</ref>
