[[File:Kūrmāsana - Tortoise Pose with Hands Facing Back.jpg|thumb|Tortoise Pose (''Kurmasana'')]] {{Contains Indic text}}
'''Kurmasana''' ({{IPAc-en|k|ʊər|ˈ|m|ɑː|s|ɑː|n|ɑː}} {{respell|koor|MAH|sah|nah}};<ref>{{cite book |last1=Budilovsky |first1=Joan |last2=Adamson |first2=Eve |title=The complete idiot's guide to yoga |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b5pE8-Oyly0C |accessdate=11 April 2011 |edition=2 |year=2000 |publisher=Penguin |isbn=978-0-02-863970-3 |page=215}}</ref> {{IPA-sa|kuːɹmɐːs̺ɐn̺ɐ}}; {{lang-sa|कूर्मासन}}; [[IAST]]: ''kūrmāsana''), '''Tortoise Pose''',{{sfn|Gray|2008|p=59}} or '''Turtle Pose'''{{sfn|Ramaswami|2005|p=77}} is an [[asana]].
==Etymology== The name comes from the Sanskrit words ''Kurma'' (कूर्म, Kūrma) meaning "turtle" or "tortoise"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ashtangayoga.info/practice/asana-vinyasa-series/primary-series-yoga-chikitsa/item/kurmasana/ | title = Kurmasana - AshtangaYoga.info | accessdate = 2011-04-11}}</ref> and ''Asana'' (आसन, Āsana) meaning "posture" or "seat".<ref name="Sinha1996">{{cite book|last=Sinha|first=S.C.|title=Dictionary of Philosophy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-zzRvh1fRzEC&pg=PA18|accessdate=9 April 2011|date=1 June 1996|publisher=Anmol Publications PVT. LTD.|isbn=978-81-7041-293-9|page=18}}</ref>
==Description==
To enter kūrmāsana a practitioner sits with the legs outstretched, feet as wide apart as possible. The knees are bent slightly, keeping the heels in contact with the floor. The body is leaned forward from the hips and the hands slid under the knees. The body leans forward (bending at the hips) to allow the hands and arms to slide sideways and backward (under the knees) until the elbows lie near the back of the knees. The heels are pushed forward and legs are straightened as much as possible. The forehead or chin is brought to touch the floor. The arms are further brought around the back to interlock the hands under the buttocks.{{sfn|Saraswati|1996|p=328}}
==Variations== Variations of Kūrmāsana include: *Supta Kūrmāsana(Sleeping Tortoise Pose)<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ashtangayoga.info/practice/asana-vinyasa-series/primary-series-yoga-chikitsa/item/supta-kurmasana/ | title = Supta Kurmasana - AshtangaYoga.info | accessdate = 2011-04-11}}</ref> *Ardha Kūrmāsana (Half Tortoise Pose)<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.bikramorlando.com/bikram_yoga_postures/Half_tortoise_pose.php | title = Bikram Yoga College of India - Ardha Kurmasana - Half tortoise pose | accessdate = 2011-04-11}}</ref> *Uttana Kūrmāsana (Upside-Down Tortoise Pose)<ref>{{cite web | url = http://yoga.omgyan.com/posture/Uttana-Kurmasana.html | title = Yoga Stretch: Uttana-Kurmasana Upside-down Tortoise | accessdate = 2011-04-11}}</ref>
