{{ethnic group| |group= Padharia / Padhariya |population = 24,000<ref name=z/> |popplace = • {{flagcountry|India}} • [[Gujarat]] |langs = • [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]], [[Kutchi language|Kutchi]] |rels= • [[Hindu]] 100% • }}
'''Padhariya''' / '''Padharia''' is name of a , [[ community]] of [[Gujarat]], [[India]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=GulBDMgxcU0C&pg=PA148&dq=padhariya&hl=en&ei=QGm_Tuz5McbKrAfm7IzWAQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CDoQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=padhariya&f=false] Encyclopaedia of backward castes, Volume 2 By M. L. Mathur, page 148</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=eMGgb5Nd_cgC&pg=PA110&dq=padhariya&hl=en&ei=QGm_Tuz5McbKrAfm7IzWAQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CD8Q6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=padhariya&f=false] Land and people of Indian states and union territories: in 36 volumes. Gujarat By S. C. Bhatt, Gopal K. Bhargava page 110</ref> They are found in [[Saurashtra (region)|Saurashtra]], [[Kutch]], [[Banaskantha]], [[Rewa Kantha|Rewakantha]] and [[Dang District, India|Dang]] regions of Gujarat.
Padharias get their name as traditional eaters of roots of [[Scirpus Groussus|''Bid'']] plant. The ' Bid ' root was unknown to almost all the people of Gujarat except Padharia and some other people. The Padharia males needed an amount of 1-1/2 to 2 [[Seer (unit)|seer]] and females needed 1-1/4 to 1-1/2 seer of 'Bid' food to keep themselves up, as noted by British authorities in their survey of 1905.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?ei=qG6_TsnbHsnorAewrdjHAQ&ct=result&id=nlbyAAAAMAAJ&dq=padharia&q=padharias#search_anchor] Agricultural ledger, Volume 11, 1905, page 580</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?ei=p2-_TtT1JYjwrQfgss28AQ&ct=result&id=nlbyAAAAMAAJ&dq=Bid+root+padharia&q=Bid+root#search_anchor] Agricultural ledger, Volume 11, 1905, page 38</ref>
At present, the total population of Padharias is estimated to be of 24,000 and they are centralized and spread only in Gujarat state of India.<ref name=z>[http://www.joshuaproject.net/people-profile.php?peo3=17807&rog3=IN Padharia]</ref> They were traditionally involved in professions like catching and selling fish as well in cultivation.<ref>Gazetteer of the Bombay Presidency: Káthiáwar, 1884</ref>
