{{Infobox Korean name | hangul = 수운교 | hanja = 水雲敎 | rr = Suungyo | mr = Suun'gyo | image = | caption = }}
'''Suunism''' ({{Korean|hangul=수운교|hanja=水雲敎|rr=Suungyo}}) is one of the [[Korea]]n [[ethnic religion]]s derived from [[Sinism]].<ref>Lee Chi-ran, p. 3</ref> It is a splinter from [[Cheondoism]] that in turn originated as an organised formation of the [[Donghak]] movement.<ref>Lee Chi-ran, p. 3</ref> "''Suwun''" was another name used by [[Choe Je-u]].<ref>Lee Chi-ran, pp. 16-20</ref> Suwunists claim to have transmitted a purer version of his teaching.<ref>Lee Chi-ran, pp. 16-20</ref>
The religion's headquarters are located in [[Daejeon]],<ref>Lee Chi-ran, p. 20</ref> where Suwun himself moved in 1929 after having preached in [[Seoul]] since 1923.<ref>Lee Chi-ran, p. 20</ref> The religion focuses on the worship of ''Okhwangsangje [[Haneullim|Hanulim]]'' (the "Great [[Jade Emperor]] of Heaven"),<ref>Lee Chi-ran, p. 20</ref> in order to make the earth a paradise through the reconnection to the One.<ref>Lee Chi-ran, p. 20</ref> An important symbol of the faith is ''Gungeul'' ("Archer Bird").<ref>Lee Chi-ran, p. 20</ref> The doctrine includes belief in the [[Maitreya]].<ref>Lee Chi-ran, pp. 20-21</ref>
